note.body:
I see the same problem on Arch Linux. It also happens with Lollypop and Showtime.

It looks to be a problem with **glib2** version **2.82.3**. After downgrading to glib2 version **2.82.2** (`sudo pacman -U /var/cache/pacman/pkg/glib2*2.82.2-1-x86_64.pkg.tar.zst`) Music, Lollypop and Showtime work fine again.

Running it like `PYTHONFAULTHANDLER=1 gnome-music` shows:
```
Fatal Python error: Segmentation fault

Current thread 0x000075455350fb80 (most recent call first):
  File "/usr/lib/python3.12/site-packages/gi/overrides/Gio.py", line 42 in run
  File "/usr/bin/gnome-music", line 97 in run_application
  File "/usr/bin/gnome-music", line 105 in main
  File "/usr/bin/gnome-music", line 110 in <module>

Extension modules: gi._gi, cairo._cairo, gi._gi_cairo, gi.overrides._gi_gst (total: 4)
Segmentation fault (core dumped)
```
The same problem about `/usr/lib/python3.12/site-packages/gi/overrides/Gio.py` line 42 is reported for Lollypop and Showtime.

**Edit:** the patch for glib2 2.28.3 proposed in https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/glib/-/issues/3559#note_2294514 fixes the issue for me.

target_title: Rethink the current views?

note.body:
I like the idea/direction behind it. Always starting with the albums view at the same point of the list is quite stale and it doesn't really invite exploring one's collection in new ways. In theory with the LocalSearch backend we have a powerful tool to do interesting queries on the local Music collection. 

One big thing that is needed for this to work is significant work to our (smart) playlist infrastructure. This is admittedly currently under maintained and not up to the task. I think the groundwork for this should happen _before_ we switch in this direction, because doing both at the same time is too much work for a cycle.
